{"title_page": "Max Liebster", "text_new": "'''Max Liebster''' (15 February 1915-28 May 2008) was a German-born victim of [[Nazi]] persecution during [[World War II]] due to his Jewish race and religion. During his imprisonment in four [[concentration camp]]s ([[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]], [[Neuengamme]], [[Auschwitz]], [[Buchenwald]]) he studied the Bible with fellow inmates that were [[Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses]] and converted to their religion, baptized in a bathtub at Buchenwald.<ref name=alst>{{cite web |title=Founders: Max Liebster |url=https://www.alst.org/pages-us/founders/max-liebster-founder.html |website=Arnold Liebster Foundation |accessdate=25 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Siegert\">{{cite news |last1=Siegert |first1=Harry |title=Max Liebster died at the age of 93 years |work=Viernheimer Tageblatt |date=29 Jul 2008}}</ref><ref name=Transport>Poland, Auschwitz-Buchenwald Transport, January 22 & 26, 1945 [database on-line]. Provo, UT, USA: Ancestry.com, 2013. Name: Max Liebstor Date of Birth: 15 Feb 1915 Place of birth: Reichenbach Profession: Dekorateur Date of Transport: 26 Jan 1945 Buchenwald Prisoner Number: 120420 Auschwitz Prisoner Number: 69733 Prisoner Nationality/Category: German/Austrian Jew (German)</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Monument to Witness Holocaust Survivor Unveiled in Germany |url=https://www.jw.org/de/aktuelle-meldungen/pressemitteilungen/nach-regionen/deutschland/denkmal-holocaust-ueberlebender/ |website=JW.org |publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society |accessdate=25 August 2019}}</ref> Liebster is also notable as the author of the book ''Crucible of Terror: A Story of Survival Through the Nazi Storm.''<ref name=alst /><ref>{{cite book |last1=Liebster |first1=Max |title=Crucible of Terror: A Story of Survival Through the Nazi Storm |date=2003 |publisher=Grammaton Press |location=New Orleans, Louisiana |isbn=9780967936628 |url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/crucible-of-terror-a-story-of-survival-through-the-nazi-storm/oclc/237852345 |accessdate=25 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=oralhistory1991>{{cite web |title=Interview with Max Liebster |url=https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/irn508771 |website=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |accessdate=25 August 2019 |date=5 Feb 1991}} Oral History Accession Number: 1992.A.0124.34 RG Number: RG-50.028.0034 Interviewer: Robert Buckley Language: English</ref><ref name=oralhistory1994>{{cite web |title=Interview with Max Liebster |url=https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/irn508835 |website=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |accessdate=25 August 2019 |date=17 May 1994}} Oral History Accession Number: 1992.A.0124.97 RG Number: RG-50.028.0097 Interviewer: Robert Buckley Language: English</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nLiebster was born to Beirech \u201cBernhard\u201d Liebster and Bertha Oppenheimer in Reichenbach, a part of [[Lautertal, Hesse]].<ref name=alst /><ref name=\"Siegert\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Max Liebster becomes an honorary citizen in his hometown |work=Bergstrasser Anzeiger |date=20 Nov 2004}}</ref><ref name=naturalization>New York, Eastern District Naturalization Petitions, Index, 1865-1957, database, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:XGX3-Q61 : 6 December 2014), Max Liebster, 1953; from \"Index to Naturalization Petitions of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York, 1865-1957,\" database, Fold3.com (http://www.fold3.com : n.d.); citing Court U.S. District Court, Brooklyn, Kings, New York, Index to Naturalization Petitions of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York, 1865-1957, NARA microfilm publication 1164 (Washington, D.C.: National Archives and Records Administration, 1991), roll 86.</ref><ref name=passenger1958>[https://www.ancestry.com/interactive/1277/42804_336057-02667/8257017 New York State, Passenger and Crew Lists, 1917-1967], database w/images (https://www.ancestry.com/ : accessed date 24 Aug 2019) The National Archives at Washington, D.C.; Washington, D.C.; NAI Number: 2848504; Record Group Title: Records of the Immigration and Naturalization Service, 1787 - 2004; Record Group Number: 85; Series Number: A3998; NARA Roll Number: 69 Name: Max Liebster Nationality: American Arrival Age: 42 Birth Date: 15 Feb 1915 Birth Place: Reichen Bach/German Hessen Arrival Date: 19 Jul 1958 Arrival Place: New York, New York, USA Destination: New York Airline Ona DC-4 Flight Number: 415</ref><ref name=oralhistory1991 /> In 1947, Liebster emigrated to America and petitioned to become an American Citizen in 1953.<ref name=\"Siegert\" /><ref name=Transport /><ref name=naturalization /><ref name=passenger1947>\"New York, New York Passenger and Crew Lists, 1909, 1925-1957,\" database with images, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:24PQ-3WP : 15 March 2018), Max Liebster, 1947; citing Immigration, New York City, New York, United States, NARA microfilm publication T715 (Washington, D.C.: National Archives and Records Administration, n.d.).</ref> In 1956, he married [[Simone Arnold Liebster|Simone Arnold]], another survivor of Nazi persecution.<ref name=\"Siegert\" /><ref name=oralhistory1991 />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://alst.org/ Arnold Liebster Foundation]\n* {{IMDb name|id=6629130}}\n* [https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/id-card/max-liebster Max Liebster] at United States Holocaust Memorial Museum\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liebster, Max}}\n[[Category:Jehovah's Witnesses people]]\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sachsenhausen concentration camp survivors| ]]\n[[Category: Neuengamme concentration camp survivors| ]]\n[[Category: Auschwitz concentration camp survivors| ]]\n[[Category: Buchenwald concentration camp survivors| ]]\n", "text_old": "'''Max Liebster''' (15 February 1915-28 May 2008) was a victim of [[Nazi]] persecution during [[World War II]] due to his Jewish race and religion. During his impr